53. patris The s is silent. Note two consecutive feet ending in -est.

55. augeor ‘I am loaded with.’ There is a bitter pleasantry in the phrase, as augere in this sense is generally applied to what is desir- able. Pamphila has been repress- ing her fears and her affection, but now she in her turn changes hertone. XVhereupon Philumena, v. 57, is moved by her sister's dis- tress to suggest that they should not give in without some effort to get their own way.
